msDesc.head: Rabanus Maurus, Commentary on the Books of Kings

watermark.note: Framed fleur-de-lis and underneath the letters: NTF (or possibly ATF).

supportDesc.foliation: Modern foliation in pencil. Lancea configere

collation.signatures: Quire signatures in Roman numerals in brown ink. (Not present on all quires.)

p.note: Top left corner, in black ink: A. 137; followed by note in pencil: Från biblioteket i Saint-Denis (kap. Delisle); centre page: National Library stamp.

binding.p: Binding of uncertain date, probably medieval or early modern. Parchment or tawed leather over wooden boards. 6 raised bands and endbands.
, bottom: National Library modern ex libris.

, in brown ink: N:o 28, Rhabani Mauri Expositiones in Libros Regum (appears to have been written over earlier text); stamped in gold: A 137; brown ink on paper label: e. 30.3.15; remains of a label at the bottom.
binding.condition: Lower endband torn. : Threads and spine liners visible.

history.provenance:
The manuscript was kept in the abbey of Saint-Denis, Paris, from an early date, but was written in Fulda according to Lehmann (1934)
.

supportDesc.foliation: Paragraphs indicated by Roman numerals in the margin.
supportDesc.condition: Holes in the parchment, but no loss of text. : text damaged by liquid spill, which also appears on other leaves. Several leaves have been damaged by cuts, e.g. on where a horizontal cut has been made below the text, or on where a strip of parchment has been cut from the bottom of the page. Between and a stub of a bifolium is visible, but there is no interruption of the text. The book block is partially cracked, e.g. between and .

layout.note: Pricking in the margin. Blind ruling.

p.note:
Top of page, in dark ink: B. 28. Spread over the upper part of page, in dark ink by a medieval hand: various exerpts, perhaps pen-trials, e.g. Matt 12:43 repeated several times, part of psalm 118:28 and others. Centre page, in dark ink by medieval hand: hic est liber beati dyonisii pro in cr-s digne cruciatur diues in igne / Vlceribus plenum quia non satiauit egenum
. Right margin in brown ink: drawing of knot-like shape. Bottom of page, in faded ink by later medieval hand: vi vii:xx xvii; below, in dark ink by later hand: Rabanus Maurus in Libros regum.

Lower margin in dark ink: two symbols that look like a C and a cross. According to Lehmann (1934)
this is typical for the abbey of Saint-Denis.

Scattered glosses by a contemporary hand, usually in the form of a single word. In the margins, references by a contemporary hand to authoritites/sources by use of 1-2 letters (e.g. B for Bede). References to Migne in pencil by a modern hand.

decoDesc.p: Main text in blackish brown ink, rubrics in red.
decoDesc.decoNote: : plain chapter initial F with interior reserved shapes over 5 lines in black. : plain chapter initial F over 5 lines in black. : plain chapter initial E over 2 lines (+ extending above the line) in black. : penwork chapter initial P over 6 lines in black. : plain initials over 1-2 lines (+ extending above or below the line) in black or red. On the initials are touched in red.

: ink drawing of two male figures. One larger (ca 10 cm) of a standing man in full figure seen from the front portrayed with fairly elaborate clothing and a crown or hat; the other small (ca 4 cm) of a bearded man in half figure profile.
: full-page drawing of a circular labyrinth-like shape. At the bottom some faint vegetative ornaments and small sitting man with a triangular hat (possibly later additions).
